I have been teaching myself how to trust in the bigger picture. I have been practicing not reacting to my familiar (usually fear-based thoughts) and instead, observing them. “all stress is caused by wanting this moment to be something it’s not. I inhale what is… I accept this time for whatever it has to show me.”

We cause our own suffering by wishing we were in a different situation, living another moment, receiving a different outcome, & so on. The power we have is to be HERE, right now. In full acceptance of what is. We have surrendered to the current outcome. If we want to move fwrd in a clear & clean way— we first have to be honest and sober about what it is—accepting our past choices & experiences that lead us here to this moment. 

THIS is the most challenging part of creating what’s to come. It’s why not everyone can do it—looking at yourself with the naked eye. It can feel overwhelming, intense & frustrating. But, LEAN in. Because on the other side of this IS the path fwrd. The choices you will now make because of what you know now. You are clearer. Your following choices have a why. 

This method goes for ANYTHING you are calling into your life. The body & health choices you want. The gym routine you wish you had. The meditation practice you resist each morning. The relationships that have to shift & change. The career outcome you want but avoid taking steps to get there. 

Honesty, acceptance, presence, and fwrd.

How you begin the start day will set the foundation for your entire life. Your mornings turn into your days; your days turn into your weeks; your weeks into your months, years & so on. It’s on the days that you resist showing up that are the days you must show up the most. Right now, we are in a massive eclipse portal that is ushering in the death of old self, the opportunity for a complete change in our life trajectory. Yes, sounds exciting, but when we are facing the sober truth & some aspects of ourselves to shed & die away, it can be highly confronting & can bring so much to the surface. Just remember that it can get loud and intense and feel super backwards right before a breakthrough. It’s in these moments that we have the power to choose what comes next by how we choose to show up now.

Workout first thing in the morning. Meditate, journal, drink a green juice & eat a healthy breakfast. Attend to the most important thing that you have to do that day. Life is full of surprises— curve balls, ya know how it goes. If you prioritize your well-being first thing you can ensure that no matter what life has presented you with that day that you took care of you.

Many ask me what I do as my form of movement…and, the answer is: Classical Pilates. My body has never been stronger, more feminine, and more beautiful.

I fell in LOVE with classical pilates a year and a half ago. I know pilates is trendy, and many of you have probably heard of this method and/or practiced it. For years, I had been doing a version of pilates. However, it wasn’t the ORIGINAL classical method. When I stumbled upon THIS specific version, my life, body, and mind all transformed. 

Classical Pilates is a method of movement that consists of body conditioning exercises invented by Joseph Pilates. This method was designed to stretch, strengthen, and balance the body. With a focus on the body-mind connection, this workout strengthens the powerhouse muscles (abs, back, glutes, thighs), and lengthens the spine. As a result, you will attain a body that moves well, a heightened mind-body connection, a healthy spine, and strong (but lean) muscles.

I learned everything I know from my teacher, Cathie. Stumbling upon her studio and taking her classes changed my body and my life. Cathie only had an in-person studio…but my gears were turning….Because I feel endlessly passionate about this practice and want to share it with you and the world, and because of my passion for Cathie’s method, I asked if she would offer her wisdom and teach for Body Fwrd… and she said yes!

My decisions came from a place of life or death. My actions were sourced from a place of feeling very unsafe and afraid. 

I knew that when I began to spearhead into this healing process, things were going to change. My relationships, my work, my ways of being. Unbecoming who you became while you were experiencing trauma is an indescribable feeling. You begin to meet parts of yourself you knew from when you were five. It takes courage to feel, acknowledge, and relive the pain that you have experienced. It’s why most of us hold it in, bypassing it. Because it fucking hurts. But, my teacher has taught me that we have to go into the fire, into the tapas, and feel the emotion for it to release. I guess you could say I have been sitting in the damn tapas for weeks.

It’s also bloody liberating and overwhelming to begin to see, feel & step into your truth. To feel inspiration again. It’s been so long since I have felt intensely lit up - but I am now meeting with my true passions. Story time…part 1. Personally, I am relieved to have survived the trials and tribulations of the past year, and I feel confident that I can overcome anything that comes my way. There were times when I wasn't sure if I could make it through, but as the year draws to a close, I sense change on the horizon. My prayers are being answered, and I have processed so much emotional baggage that I feel a sense of renewal and space for new experiences and growth.
 
Over the past few months, I have delved deep into myself and undergone the most profound 'awakening' of my life. It has been a challenging journey, forcing me to confront my vulnerabilities and push past my limits while facing the unknown and watching what I thought I knew crumble away. Although I sometimes question whether I should have opened this Pandora's box of awakening, the truth is that I had no choice. My life path has always been one of self-discovery and growth, and I have always sought the truth for the sake of love.
 
Until the last quarter of this year...my journey has been lonely, as I have never felt like I fit in or belonged. I have often felt judged (that could have been me judging myself), and in my quest for truth, I have searched in many places that have yet to yield results. However, in 2023, when my Saturn's return ushered into my life, I prayed for true awakening, and what I found was not the dream life I had envisioned but a process of pure deconstruction. Everything that was not true crumbled away, leaving me facing uncomfortable truths and feelings I had avoided. Yet, I persevered.
 
The most challenging aspect of this journey has been carving a new path forward and discovering a new sense of self that is true to the depths of me and unbecoming of who I am not. Everything that used to be a crutch or coping mechanism is no longer available to me, leaving me to break deep karmic, ancestral, and lineage cycles and face the pain that has been passed down and has resided inside of my body. *continued in comments below

Story time…part 2. I must begin by saying that I have felt shattered, defeated, and experienced physical pain throughout my entire being. The depth of heartbreak and loneliness I've felt is beyond words. I have felt suppressed and robbed of my true identity, unable to express who I really am. And, when I realized that I have been living this way...I have felt so angry that that even happened in the first place!
 
As I've explored these emotions and delved deeper, I have found that they originate from various traumas in my childhood and early adulthood. Some of these traumas were actual events or truths from my upbringing, some have been things I have done to myself, and some have been passed down through my bloodline. Other people's never-processed or felt traumas led me to believe they were my truths.
 
Since the age of 14, I've been in a constant fight or flight mode, making it challenging to address and acknowledge the pain and patterns I've carried for so long. But as I've safely begun to explore and feel my emotions, my entire being has begun to un-thaw.
 
I share this with you because if you're experiencing something similar, please know it's okay. Although everything may seem fine on the outside, the pain within can be overwhelming. You may not be able to pinpoint one specific event or person to blame, but it's crucial to acknowledge that the feelings you're experiencing are valid. Allow yourself to feel broken and vulnerable because the only way out is through. Through my journey, I've understood that what we seek can only be found within ourselves. Every feeling we seek is already within us, and it's essential to take the time to explore and process our (suppressed) emotions so that we can set ourselves free.

Over the last two months, I've pressured myself to determine what's next and 'pull it together.' However, I've realized that I couldn't do that until now, and it's okay to allow yourself to be in the absolute MUCK of your emotions. *continued in comments below

Story time…part 3.

Alright..I saved the (longest) bit of this story for the last. Let's dive in:
 
I have frequently pondered why existing on this planet has proven to be such a challenging feat for me. More often than not, I have felt disconnected from a life that is grounded and rooted. This disconnection has led me to explore numerous passions, locations, friendships, and endeavors. However, I have never been able to fully anchor myself to any of these things, leaving me feeling like I am not living a stable life, yet that has always been what I have craved the most.
 
Through various experiences as of late, such as feminine embodiment work, a good ol' dark night of the soul, and by asking God to guide me, I have discovered that my failure to fully accept my life path (and myself) has prevented me from owning my life, voice, and stake on this earth.
 
I have allowed myself to go through the process of feeling like a wanderer, experiencing the pain that comes with it. I have let myself feel anger at not being able to establish stable roots that keep me grounded. Feeling lost has been the most challenging aspect for me.
 
However, at some point, you have to be firm with yourself and say enough. As the year ends, I have given myself an ultimatum: it's time to be present and claim my life. My journey of self-discovery is far from over, and I will continue to face challenges, but it is time for me to stand with both feet firmly on the ground.
 
I have been afraid to use my inner knowing and voice publicly and have even dreamt of people closing my throat up, which has shown me that this fear runs deep. It is time for me to break free from this suppression in this lifetime.
 
No matter what I am going through, I have found that returning to my body allows me to feel at home. It was during one of these moments that I discovered my path forward. It involves planting roots on this earth that I can nourish, grow, embody, and share with others. *continued in comments
